 <br><br>
Politics suspected in Arlington burials<br>
------------------<br>
By Rowan Scarborough<br>
THE WASHINGTON TIMES<br>
November 20, 1997<br>
--------------------<br>
House probe has uncovered cases of suspected &quot;favoritism&quot; by the Clinton administration in granting burial in the restricted Arlington National Cemetery in Virginia to people who never served in the military. <br>
. . . . Rep. Terry Everett, Alabama Republican and chairman of the House Veterans' Affairs subcommittee on oversight and investigations, said Army Secretary Togo West has granted an unprecedented 60 waivers to the burial rules since 1993.<br>
. . . . Of those, he said, 10 have &quot;no rhyme nor reason&quot; for the honor of burial in what war veterans revere as sacred ground.<br>
. . . . In all 10 cases, the congressman's spokesman said, the Arlington superintendent recommended denial but was overruled by Mr. West.<br>
. . . . Mr. West issued waivers based on recommendations from Assistant Army Secretary Sara Lister, who said in a June 12 letter to Mr. Everett that Arlington burial policy &quot;falls under my purview.&quot; Mrs. Lister resigned last week after her remark that Marines are &quot;extremists&quot; angered veterans and members of Congress.<br>
. . . . The Army Times reported in June that Mr. West has waived the burial rules at Arlington almost triple the rate of the two previous administrations under Ronald Reagan and George Bush and has granted the highest number since the exception process began 30 years ago.<br>
. . . . Mr. West denied to the publication that political favoritism was a motivating factor.<br>
. . . . But Mr. Everett, whose probe began in June, said this week in an interview that &quot;there are some folks in Arlington that shouldn't be buried there. There would obviously have to be some favoritism or they wouldn't have been given the waiver. ... These are people that never served in the service.&quot;<br>
. . . . He said his subcommittee has not yet determined whether any of the questionable waivers involved people -- or their family members -- who donated money to the Clinton campaign or the Democratic Party.<br>
. . . . Mr. Everett said that question will be answered in January, when his staff plans to compare the waiver list with a campaign contributor database.<br>
. . . . Insight magazine, a sister publication of The Washington Times, this week raises the possibility that Mr. West granted waivers to big Clinton-Gore campaign donors. The magazine does not identify the donors.<br>
. . . . At the White House, presidential counsel Lanny J. Davis called the account &quot;scurrilous and untrue.&quot;<br>
. . . . &quot;The president and this administration consider Arlington National Cemetery and other national and veterans cemeteries across the country to be hallowed ground,&quot; he said. &quot;It would be outrageous for anyone to grant or influence the granting of exceptions under the rules for burial at national cemeteries because of political or fund-raising considerations.&quot;<br>
. . . . Mr. Davis said Mr. Clinton has granted just four exceptions for burial at Arlington -- for a Supreme Court justice, the wife of another Supreme Court justice, an Army veteran who was a Drug Enforcement Administration agent killed on a mission in Peru and a Marine Corps veteran killed in the line of duty as a Washington police officer. He said the White House may have provided information to the Army in connection with burial requests for other people.<br>
. . . . The Army yesterday released a statement again flatly denying that political considerations played any role in signing a waiver. The charges &quot;are untrue and a disservice to American military men and women, past and present.&quot;<br>
. . . . A two-page fact sheet issued by the Army said Mr. West has approved 58 requests for exceptions to the burial policy at Arlington National Cemetery since November 1993, when he took office. There was no explanation for the difference between the Army's number and Mr. Everett's. The statement said Mr. Clinton granted one exception in 1993 and three in 1994.<br>
. . . . Maj. Gen. John G. Meyer Jr., chief of Army public affairs, said in a statement that &quot;allegations that exceptions for burial at Arlington National Cemetery are being granted for political considerations, or, worse, for political contributions, are untrue, and a disservice to American military men and women, past and present.&quot;<br>
. . . . An Army official who spoke to the Associated Press on the condition of anonymity said most of the exceptions were to the rule that a veteran's widow who remarries may not be buried in the cemetery.<br>
. . . . The Army statement said one government official who had no military service was granted burial in Arlington because he was killed in the line of duty while working for the State Department. The second was described as playing a crucial role in several administrations, including service in war zones during World War II and a key role during the Cuban Missile Crisis.<br>
. . . . Neither the Army nor the House panel will release the identities of those granted waivers.<br>
. . . . Mr. Everett said he may publicize the names at hearings set for early next year.<br>
. . . . &quot;We have some waivers granted. We can't find any criteria why they were granted,&quot; the congressman said. &quot;We would like to have some answers from the Department of the Army on why those waivers were granted and if there was any favoritism shown. Obviously, the way I look at it, I don't understand how they got permission to be buried there if there wasn't any favoritism.&quot;<br>
. . . . With more than 240,000 people interred there, new plots are hard to come by at the hilly 200-acre cemetery overlooking the Potomac River. Arlington enforces a strict list of criteria for burial rights. They include length of service, the type of war decorations and whether the person held high public office.<br>
. . . . Veterans of the Army, Air Force, Navy, Marines and Coast Guard are routinely denied a grave site.<br>
. . . . Mr. Everett said the House probe began based on complaints from the families of veterans and government whistleblowers. He began his investigation June 4 in a letter to Mr. West requesting &quot;copies of all applications for waivers, any accompanying documentation and all memoranda, letters and any other documents&quot; relating to Arlington.<br>
. . . . Mrs. Lister wrote back, saying the Army has a &quot;flash&quot; procedure for each waiver request but has &quot;no formal exception criteria.&quot; She urged Mr. Everett not to release the names of those who received waivers.<br>
. . . . Responding to the Insight story, Sen. John McCain, Arizona Republican, yesterday called on Mr. West and the Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee to investigate as well.<br>
. . . . &quot;Frankly, I find it difficult to believe that such a despicable practice could possibly have occurred,&quot; Mr. McCain, a former Navy pilot and prisoner of war in Vietnam, wrote to Mr. West. &quot;The number of instances cited in the report is small. But even if one occurred, it would be shameful example of political pandering that demeans the administration and dishonors the service of our nation's veterans.&quot;<br>
. . . . Said Rep. Spencer Bachus, Alabama Republican, who wrote Mr. West asking him whether he had permitted civilians to be buried in national cemeteries: &quot;It's nothing short of a national disgrace if it happened.&quot;<br><br>
This article is based in part on wire service reports.<br>
Cook Barela, Sgt. USMC Vietnam 1967-1968<br>
